---
/**
 * Hub: saver's credit. Eligibility + maximum only — the exact 50/20/10 tier
 * thresholds are not in the dataset, and the page says so. Worked example by
 * saversCredit().
 */
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import SaversCreditCalculator from '../../components/calculators/SaversCreditCalculator.tsx';
import { saversCredit } from '../../lib/credits';
import { formatMoney } from '../../lib/tax-engine';

const single = saversCredit(30000, 'single', 2000);
const mfj = saversCredit(50000, 'mfj', 4000);
const over = saversCredit(45000, 'single', 2000);
---

<Base
  title="Saver's credit calculator 2026 — who qualifies"
  description="Check 2026 saver's credit eligibility: up to $1,000 ($2,000 joint) for retirement contributions, by AGI and filing status. Non-refundable."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <p class="hero-label">2026 tax year</p>
    <h1>Saver's credit calculator</h1>
    <p class="tagline">A credit that pays you back for saving for retirement — if your income is modest enough.</p>
  </section>

  <p>
    The saver's credit (the retirement savings contributions credit) rewards
    lower-income workers for paying into a 401(k) or IRA. It is worth 50%, 20% or
    10% of up to {formatMoney(2000)} of contributions ({formatMoney(4000)} if
    married filing jointly), depending on your income — a maximum of {formatMoney(1000)}
    ({formatMoney(2000)} joint). This checks whether you qualify and the most you
    could get.
  </p>

  <SaversCreditCalculator client:load />

  <h2>Worked example — who qualifies</h2>
  <p>
    Eligibility turns on adjusted gross income and filing status:
  </p>
  <table class="data-table">
    <thead><tr><th>Filer</th><th>AGI</th><th>Eligible?</th><th>Maximum credit</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Single, {formatMoney(2000)} contributed</td><td>{formatMoney(30000)}</td><td>Yes</td><td>{formatMoney(single.maxPossibleCredit)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Single, {formatMoney(2000)} contributed</td><td>{formatMoney(45000)}</td><td>No (over {formatMoney(40250)})</td><td>{formatMoney(over.maxPossibleCredit)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Married joint, {formatMoney(4000)} contributed</td><td>{formatMoney(50000)}</td><td>Yes</td><td>{formatMoney(mfj.maxPossibleCredit)}</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    The single filer at {formatMoney(30000)} could get up to {formatMoney(single.maxPossibleCredit)},
    but the same filer at {formatMoney(45000)} is over the {formatMoney(40250)} income
    limit and gets nothing. The married couple's higher {formatMoney(80500)} limit
    keeps them eligible at {formatMoney(50000)}.
  </p>

  <div class="faq" data-review="legal">
    <h3>Why does this show a maximum rather than my exact credit?</h3>
    <p>
      The credit rate is 50%, 20% or 10% depending on which income tier you fall in,
      and the exact 2026 tier thresholds are set annually and are not yet in our
      verified dataset. Rather than guess them, this calculator shows the maximum
      (the 50% tier) and your eligibility. Your Form 8880 or the IRS instructions
      give the tier for your income.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>What contributions count?</h3>
    <p>
      Contributions to a traditional or Roth IRA, a 401(k), 403(b), 457, SIMPLE or
      SEP, and to an ABLE account, up to {formatMoney(2000)} per person
      ({formatMoney(4000)} on a joint return). Rollovers do not count.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>What are the 2026 income limits?</h3>
    <p data-review="legal">
      The credit disappears above {formatMoney(40250)} of AGI for single filers,
      {formatMoney(60375)} for head of household, and {formatMoney(80500)} for married
      filing jointly. Below those, a lower income means a higher credit rate.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Is the saver's credit refundable?</h3>
    <p>
      No. It reduces the tax you owe but is not paid back beyond that. A worker with
      very low income and little tax liability may not be able to use the full
      credit — an irony of a credit aimed at lower earners.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Can students claim it?</h3>
    <p>
      No. Full-time students, anyone claimed as a dependent, and those under 18 are
      ineligible, regardless of income or contributions.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>Related tools</h2>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    <li><a href="/paycheck-calculator/">Paycheck calculator</a> — model a 401(k) contribution</li>
    <li><a href="/benefits-tax-calculator/">Benefits and retirement</a></li>
    <li><a href="/earned-income-credit-calculator/">Earned income credit calculator</a></li>
  </ul>

  <p class="results-note">
    Eligibility estimate for the 2026 tax year. The exact credit needs your income
    tier from Form 8880. Not tax advice.
  </p>
</Base>
